data.name: ValidateKey.HelpString
data.value: Clicking this button will validate your Listen Key by contacting Digitally Imported's, JazzRadio's or SKY.FM's servers. RockRadio doesn't use Listen Keys so the Key will be validated against Digitally Imported's servers instead.

data.name: ListenLink.HelpString
data.value: Clicking this link will open your default web browser pointing to your My Listen Key page, where you'll be able to check your current Listen Key and reset it. RockRadio doesn't use Listen Keys so this link will open the Digitally Imported page instead.

data.name: ListenKey.HelpString
data.value: Write your Listen key to enable support for My Favorites and, if you have a Premium account, enable support for Premium formats. You can use the Validate button to check if your Listen Key is a Premium one or not.

data.name: FileFormat.HelpString
data.value: Select your preferred file format for listening to Digitally Imported, SKY.FM or JazzRadio. The following file formats are supported for FREE accounts: MP3 at 96 kbits/sec, AAC-HE at 40 kbits/sec, Windows Media at 40 kbits/sec. The following formats are supported for PREMIUM accounts: MP3 at 256 and 128 kbits/sec, AAC-HE at 128, 64 and 40 kbits/sec, Windows Media at 128 and 64 kbits/sec (Windows Media at 64 kbits/sec not available for JazzRadio). Currently RockRadio is in Beta stage and only supports MP3 at 96kbits/sec.

data.name: HighQualityVis.HelpString
data.value: Selecting this check box will apply an anti-aliasing effect on the visualisations to make the lines look smoother. The effect won't be noticeable on all visualisations and it may use quite a lot of CPU power.

data.name: Label11.Text
data.value: You can set your own custom hotkeys to do several operations while the application is minimised to the tray area; to customise hotkeys simply select the check box of the action you want to set and then press your desired keys. To return to the default hotkey simply clear it.

data.name: AutoEq.HelpString
data.value: This button adjusts any equalizer settings so that no positive amplification is applied to any of the frequency bands, i.e. 0dB is the “highest” value. This may help reduce possible distortion without changing the “shape” of the frequency band, e.g. if +5dB is the highest level of amplification, all frequency bands are lowered by -5dB, so -8dB changes to -13dB and so on. Please note that you will have to raise your volume after applying this adjustment since the frequency response will be quieter.
